Because the Subscription name is just an object name, not the current installed version.

For example:

ocs-operator-stable-4.19-redhat-operator-index-openshift-marketplace

is the metadata.name of the Subscription resource. OLM does not rename Subscription objects when you change channels or upgrade versions.

Think of it like this:

metadata:
  name: ocs-operator-stable-4.19-redhat-operator-index-openshift-marketplace
spec:
  channel: stable-4.20

The name stays the same, but the subscription tracks whatever channel is configured.

What matters is:

oc get sub ocs-operator-stable-4.19-redhat-operator-index-openshift-marketplace \
-n openshift-storage -o jsonpath='{.spec.channel}'

You should get:

stable-4.20

And the installed CSV is:

oc get sub ocs-operator-stable-4.19-redhat-operator-index-openshift-marketplace \
-n openshift-storage -o jsonpath='{.status.installedCSV}'

Expected:

ocs-operator.v4.20.10-rhodf

That's the actual version OLM has installed.

You can also verify directly:

oc get csv -n openshift-storage | grep ocs-operator

Output:

ocs-operator.v4.20.10-rhodf   Succeeded

So:

Field	Value

Subscription Name	ocs-operator-stable-4.19-...
Channel	stable-4.20
Installed CSV	ocs-operator.v4.20.10-rhodf
StorageCluster Version	4.20.10


The 4.19 in the Subscription name is merely a historical artifact from when the subscription was first created. It has no effect on the currently installed operator version.

If it bothers you, you could delete and recreate the Subscription with a new name, but there is no technical benefit and it is generally not recommended on a running ODF cluster. The current state is correct.
